Think of the tiny little and probably grossly overlooked plot point: there's (probably) a fully functional spaceship capable of interstellar travel orbiting the Anthroworld. On that premise alone you could plunge the entire setting into an equivalent of space race, with a prize just hanging up there for the fastest one to grab. Depending on how the factions in the setting work, that could spell all kinds of trouble for our charming protagonists, as well as the cast of more or less wacky characters, to get into, not to mention how any single piece of tech on board could potentially bump the anthros' research tree up an age or two. Now, let's assume that the on board computer was programmed to send a beacon or a transmission of sorts back to the main planet when sapient lifeforms of nonhuman origin (or are they?) are recognized and logged into the system, depending on all kinds of factors we can find a good ol' humanity coming to the """rescue""" (perhaps space oil is included), some kind of new type of spess dwelling humanity showing up because in actuality eons have passed since the protag left on his journey or even have the signal intercepted by some actually alien aliens, ready to crash the party for one reason or another. Or perhaps protag didn't actually discover a new world but came back home, as a living, breathing relic of an age long past. There's actually a lot of potential in what little there is shown about the setting, the foundation is solid and ready to build upon, soil only as rich as the creativity of the author, more of which is yet to be seen, assuming that he indeed does continue on with that premise.
